<subSubSection pageId="23" pageNumber="22" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="23.[192,1441,834,1083]" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[192,349,834,858]" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Discussion.</emphasis>
This is the largest tribe of antlions with species in all parts of the temperate to tropical world except for the Neantarctic Region (
<collectingCountry box="[694,761,866,890]" name="Chile" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Chile</collectingCountry>
and southern 
<collectingCountry box="[935,1065,866,890]" name="Argentina" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Argentina</collectingCountry>
). This tribe is characterized by having the forewing vein 1A bending at sharp angle toward 3A (except some 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Tillyard. Probably" authorityYear="1916" box="[1143,1282,898,922]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Xantholeon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1143,1282,898,922]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Xantholeon</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
), only 1 or 2 presectoral crossveins in the hindwing, and lacking the male pilula axillaris. In 
<collectingCountry box="[1142,1257,930,954]" name="Australia" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Australia</collectingCountry>
there are three genera containing cave dwelling antlions. These are 
<taxonomicName authority="Banks" authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1931" box="[812,1011,962,986]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Eophanes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[812,929,962,986]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Eophanes</emphasis>
Banks
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Tillyard" authorityName="Tillyard" authorityYear="1916" box="[1021,1244,962,986]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Stenoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1021,1137,962,986]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Stenoleon</emphasis>
Tillyard
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Tillyard. Probably" authorityName="Tillyard. Probably" authorityYear="1916" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Xantholeon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1304,1441,962,986]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Xantholeon</emphasis>
Tillyard. Probably
</taxonomicName>
all the species of these genera are adapted to living in caves or rock overhangs. Elsewhere, cave dwelling nemoleontine genera are known only from the Western Hemisphere represented by 
<taxonomicName authority="Banks" authorityName="Banks" authorityYear="1901" box="[229,444,1058,1082]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Eremoleon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="23" pageNumber="22" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[229,360,1058,1082]" italics="true" pageId="23" pageNumber="22">Eremoleon</emphasis>
Banks
</taxonomicName>
which is a speciose genus with nearly all of the reared species living in caves.
</paragraph>
